The concept of [area](/Area) enclosed by a [circle](/Circle) is one of those foundational geometric truths that seems so self-evident, yet its precise quantification, particularly the ubiquitous [constant](/Constant_(mathematics)) [π](/Pi), reveals layers of mathematical elegance and historical struggle. In [geometry](/Geometry), the region contained within a circle of [radius](/Radius) *r* is precisely quantified by the formula *πr*<sup>2</sup>. Here, the Greek letter [π](/Pi) (pi) does the heavy lifting, representing an unchanging ratio – specifically, the ratio of a circle's [circumference](/Circumference) to its [diameter](/Diameter). Its value, an unending and non-repeating decimal, begins approximately as 3.1415926535897932384626433...

This seemingly simple formula underpins countless calculations, from the mundane task of calculating the surface area of a pizza to the complexities of [celestial mechanics](/Celestial_mechanics). It is part of [a series of articles](/Category:Pi) dedicated to exploring this mathematical marvel.

### Uses

The utility of π extends far beyond the mere measurement of circles, permeating various branches of mathematics and physics.

*   **Area of a circle**: As discussed, it's the fundamental measure of the space a circle occupies.
*   [**Circumference**](/Circumference): Intimately linked, the circumference of a circle is given by 2π*r*, or π*D* where *D* is the diameter, reflecting π's very definition.
*   [**Use in other formulae**](/List_of_formulae_involving_%CF%80): Its presence is felt across diverse fields, appearing in everything from wave equations to probability distributions, a testament to its fundamental role in describing the universe.

### Properties

The nature of π is as profound as its prevalence.

*   [**Irrationality**](/Proof_that_%CF%80_is_irrational): One of its most crucial properties is that it cannot be expressed as a simple fraction *p/q*, meaning its decimal representation is infinite and non-repeating. This was a significant discovery, proven by [Johann Heinrich Lambert](/Johann_Heinrich_Lambert) in 1761.
*   [**Transcendence**](/Lindemann%E2%80%93Weierstrass_theorem): Even more remarkably, π is a [transcendental number](/Transcendental_number), meaning it is not the root of any non-zero polynomial equation with rational coefficients. This profound property, proven by [Ferdinand von Lindemann](/Ferdinand_von_Lindemann) in 1882, definitively settled the ancient problem of [squaring the circle](/Squaring_the_circle) with only a [compass and straightedge](/Straightedge_and_compass_construction)—it's impossible.

### Value

Pinning down the exact value of π has been an obsession for mathematicians for millennia, a quest that has pushed the boundaries of numerical approximation.

*   [**Less than 22/7**](/Proof_that_22/7_exceeds_%CF%80): A common approximation, 22/7, is a remarkably good one for many practical purposes, but it's important to remember it's slightly larger than the true value of π.
*   [**Approximations**](/Approximations_of_%CF%80): From ancient geometric methods to modern supercomputers, the history of mathematics is littered with increasingly precise approximations of π.
*   [**Milü**](/Mil%C3%BC): The Chinese mathematician [Zu Chongzhi](/Zu_Chongzhi) provided the fraction 355/113, an astonishingly accurate approximation for its time, known as Milü.
*   [**Madhava's correction term**](/Madhava%27s_correction_term): The Indian mathematician [Madhava of Sangamagrama](/Madhava_of_Sangamagrama) developed an infinite series that allowed for unprecedented accuracy in calculating π, centuries before similar methods were discovered in Europe.
*   [**Memorization**](/Piphilology): The allure of π is such that many dedicate themselves to memorizing its digits, a practice known as [piphilology](/Piphilology), often using mnemonic devices.

### People

The story of π is a grand tapestry woven by the minds of some of history's greatest thinkers.

*   [**Archimedes**](/Method_of_exhaustion): The ancient Greek polymath who pioneered the [method of exhaustion](/Method_of_exhaustion) to approximate π by inscribing and circumscribing polygons.
*   [**Liu Hui**](/Liu_Hui%27s_%CF%80_algorithm): A brilliant Chinese mathematician who refined Archimedes' method, developing his own [π algorithm](/Liu_Hui%27s_%CF%80_algorithm).
*   [**Zu Chongzhi**](/Zu_Chongzhi): The aforementioned Chinese mathematician famous for his Milü approximation.
*   [**Aryabhata**](/Aryabhata): An early Indian mathematician and astronomer who gave a value of π that was accurate to four decimal places.
*   [**Madhava**](/Madhava_of_Sangamagrama): The founder of the Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics, whose work on infinite series was revolutionary.
*   [**Jamshīd al-Kāshī**](/Jamsh%C4%ABd_al-K%C4%81sh%C4%AB): A Persian mathematician and astronomer who calculated π to 16 decimal places in the 15th century.
*   [**Ludolph van Ceulen**](/Ludolph_van_Ceulen): A German-Dutch mathematician who spent much of his life calculating π to 35 decimal places, so significant that it was engraved on his tombstone.
*   [**François Viète**](/Fran%C3%A7ois_Vi%C3%A8te): A French mathematician who derived the first infinite product formula for π.
*   [**Seki Takakazu**](/Seki_Takakazu): A Japanese mathematician who derived an algorithm for π similar to the [Leibniz formula](/Leibniz_formula_for_%CF%80).
*   [**Takebe Kenko**](/Takebe_Kenko): Another Japanese mathematician who calculated π to 41 decimal places using power series.
*   [**William Jones**](/William_Jones_(mathematician)): The Welsh mathematician who first used the Greek letter π to denote the ratio in 1706.
*   [**John Machin**](/John_Machin): An English mathematician who developed a rapidly converging series for π, used for calculations for centuries.
*   [**William Shanks**](/William_Shanks): An English amateur mathematician who famously (and erroneously) calculated π to 707 decimal places by hand in the 19th century.
*   [**Srinivasa Ramanujan**](/Srinivasa_Ramanujan): The self-taught Indian mathematical genius who discovered numerous new formulas for π.
*   [**John Wrench**](/John_Wrench): An American mathematician involved in early computer calculations of π.
*   [**Chudnovsky brothers**](/Chudnovsky_brothers): Modern mathematicians who developed algorithms and used supercomputers to calculate π to billions of digits.
*   [**Yasumasa Kanada**](/Yasumasa_Kanada): A Japanese mathematician who held many records for calculating digits of π using powerful computers.

### History

The pursuit of π is an ancient and ongoing saga, a testament to humanity's drive to understand the fundamental constants of the universe.

*   [**Chronology**](/Chronology_of_computation_of_%CF%80): The detailed timeline of how humanity has progressively refined its understanding and calculation of π is a fascinating journey through mathematical history.
*   [**A History of Pi**](/A_History_of_Pi): Petr Beckmann's seminal work on the subject offers a comprehensive and engaging narrative of this enduring mathematical quest.

### In culture

π has transcended its mathematical origins to become a recognizable cultural icon, a symbol of intellectual pursuit and mathematical beauty.

*   [**Indiana pi bill**](/Indiana_pi_bill): A rather infamous episode in 1897 where the Indiana state legislature nearly passed a bill legally defining π as an incorrect rational value, highlighting the dangers of legislative interference in scientific matters.
*   [**Pi Day**](/Pi_Day): Celebrated annually on March 14th (3/14), it's a playful ode to the constant, often involving the consumption of pie.

### Related topics

The influence of π extends to a wide array of mathematical concepts and problems.

*   [**Squaring the circle**](/Squaring_the_circle): The ancient geometric problem, definitively proven impossible due to π's transcendence.
*   [**Basel problem**](/Basel_problem): A famous problem in mathematical analysis, first solved by [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler), whose solution involved π.
*   [**Six nines in π**](/Six_nines_in_pi): The appearance of six consecutive nines in π's decimal expansion, a curious numerical coincidence that sparked much interest.
