### Three-dimensional](/Three-dimensional_space)

Objects possessing length, width, and height, occupying space.

*   [**Surface area**](/Surface_area): The total area of the exposed surfaces of a three-dimensional object.
*   [**Volume**](/Volume): The measure of the space occupied by a three-dimensional object.

#### [Polyhedron](/Polyhedron)

A three-dimensional solid with flat polygonal faces, straight edges, and sharp corners or vertices.

*   [**Platonic Solid**](/Platonic_Solid): A convex polyhedron whose faces are congruent regular polygons, with the same number of faces meeting at each vertex. There are only five: tetrahedron, cube, octahedron, dodecahedron, icosahedron.
*   [**Tetrahedron**](/Tetrahedron): A polyhedron with four triangular faces.
*   [**cuboid**](/Cuboid): A box-shaped polyhedron with six rectangular faces.
*   [**Cube**](/Cube): A cuboid with six square faces.
*   [**Octahedron**](/Octahedron): A polyhedron with eight triangular faces.
*   [**Dodecahedron**](/Dodecahedron): A polyhedron with twelve pentagonal faces.
*   [**Icosahedron**](/Icosahedron): A polyhedron with twenty triangular faces.
*   [**Pyramid**](/Pyramid_(geometry)): A polyhedron formed by connecting a polygonal base to a point, called the apex.

#### [Solid of revolution](/Solid_of_revolution)

A three-dimensional shape formed by rotating a two-dimensional shape around an axis.

*   [**Sphere**](/Sphere): A perfectly round three-dimensional object, where every point on its surface is equidistant from its center.
*   [**Great circle**](/Great_circle): Any circle on a sphere whose center is the center of the sphere.
*   [**Cylinder**](/Cylinder_(geometry)): A three-dimensional solid with two parallel circular bases and a curved surface connecting them.
*   [**Cone**](/Cone): A three-dimensional solid with a circular base and a single vertex (apex).

### Four](/Four-dimensional_space)-/other-dimensional

Exploring dimensions beyond our immediate perception.

*   [**4-polytope**](/4-polytope): The four-dimensional analogue of a [polyhedron](/Polyhedron).
*   [**Simplex**](/Simplex): A generalization of a triangle to arbitrary dimensions.
*   [**5-cell**](/5-cell): The simplest [4-polytope](/4-polytope), a four-dimensional analogue of a tetrahedron.
*   [**Hypercube**](/Hypercube): The n-dimensional analogue of a square and a cube.
*   [**Tesseract**](/Tesseract): The four-dimensional hypercube.
*   [**n-sphere**](/N-sphere): The n-dimensional analogue of a circle and a sphere.
*   [**Hypersphere**](/Hypersphere): Another term for an n-sphere, often used to refer specifically to the surface.

